The acting is horrendous to say the least. 1/3 into the movie I wanted to switch it off but kept going waiting for the climax, which btw never comes. I began regarding the movie as a test of my willpower to watch the whole thing.The movie ends with a tiny rediculous fight scene with a screwdriver and then fades to black. text: Blackhat is a solid movie. I understand the¬†characters looking at codes on monitors does not make for the most riveting viewing, but knowing people who hold similar jobs under government contractors, the technology deception is fairly accurate. I also like how the film attempts to break the stereotypes of the two male leads.¬†Hollywood tends to view hackers not as physique and a bit socially awkward and Asians¬†who¬†talk¬†with a poor accent. Michael Mann did a great job with the movie and like the chemistry between Chris and Lee Hom, but it failed to capture the audience's appeal towards hacking.  Chris Hemsworth's character reminds me of actor Dolph Lundgren. The actor¬†received a full ride to MIT in 1983, but his relationship with actress Grace Jones while working as a nightclub bouncer in Sydney convinced him to give acting a shot and moved to New York instead.

text: i'd love it if michael mann would make a movie that was fun to watch, or at least more entertaining than mildly interesting. his movies are generally pretty smart, but also pretty stylized from what i remember. for me, the action in this one feels completely out of place and unnecessary, and many times i was left wondering why these people did things the way they did. it's as the characters said, 'okay, what's the most logical thing to do? great, now let's do the complete opposite of that and see what happens!'   to me, you have to dig deep and awaken your inner pretentious artist to find a ton to love about this flick. it was if mann knew when we were getting really bored with the admittedly dull plot and spiced it up with a little action (and the worst love scene ever), but remove the pedigree and style and you have a fairly predictable movie. i mean, y'all know one plus one equals two, right? (unless you use common core, in which case blue + Q - the speed of imagination in a vacuum divided by banana = 2.) well, in that sense there shouldn't be any real surprises here (there is one thing that did surprise me, but i won't spoil it, just that it was entirely unnecessary ~ surprising, but rather a storytelling head-scratcher).   add everything, plus the fact you find yourself leaning forward to hear the dialogue over the music, and i feel as if it falls into a lot of what i recall mann's movies to be like, smart and competently made, yet failing to commit to being one thing or another and leaving me with split feelings about as a result.
